Guide: Accessing AWS EC2 Instances via PuTTY & MTPuTTY
======================================================
Prerequisites
------------------------------------------------------
PuTTY & PuTTYgen installed on your local machine.
MTPuTTY installed (for tabbed management).
An active AWS EC2 Instance with a Public IP.
The Key Pair (.pem file) downloaded from the AWS Console.
------------------------------------------------------
Phase 1: Key Conversion (.pem to .ppk)
------------------------------------------------------
AWS provides keys in .pem format, but PuTTY requires .ppk.
Open PuTTYgen.
Click Load and navigate to your <your-key-name>.pem file.
Note: You may need to change the file type filter in the explorer window to "All Files (.)" to see the .pem file.
Once the message "Successfully imported foreign key" appears, click OK.
Click Save private key.
When asked if you want to save without a passphrase, click Yes (or add one for extra security).
Save the file as <your-key-name>.ppk in a secure folder.
------------------------------------------------------
Phase 2: Configuring the PuTTY Session
------------------------------------------------------
Before using MTPuTTY, we must create a "Master Profile" in PuTTY.
1. Basic Connection
Host Name (or IP address): Enter the Public IP of your instance (e.g., 3.xx.xx.xx).
Port: 22
Connection type: SSH
2. Authentication (The Key)
In the left Category tree, expand Connection > SSH > Auth.
Select Credentials.
Under Private key file for authentication, click Browse and select your newly created .ppk file.
3. Auto-Login (Optional but Recommended)
Go to Connection > Data.
In Auto-login username, type the default user for your Linux distribution:
Ubuntu: ubuntu
Amazon Linux / RHEL: ec2-user
Debian: admin
4. Save the Session
Go back to the Session category (top of the list).
Under Saved Sessions, type a descriptive name (e.g., AWS-Prod-Server-01).
Click Save.
------------------------------------------------------
Phase 3: Organizing with MTPuTTY
------------------------------------------------------
MTPuTTY allows you to run multiple PuTTY sessions in tabs and "blast" commands to all of them at once.
Open MTPuTTY.
Importing: If your saved PuTTY sessions don't appear automatically, go to Servers > Import from PuTTY.
Grouping: * Right-click Servers and select New Folder (e.g., "Ansible-Cluster").
Drag and drop your servers into this folder.
Connecting: Double-click the server name to open it in a new tab.
------------------------------------------------------
Troubleshooting Checklist
------------------------------------------------------
Timeout Error? Check your AWS Security Group. Ensure Inbound Rules allow Port 22 from your current Public IP.
Permission Denied (publickey)? Ensure the username (e.g., ubuntu) matches the OS of the instance and that the correct .ppk file is linked.
Sudo Issues? If you need to run admin commands without a password once logged in, remember to add your user to the sudoers file using sudo visudo.

